Below is a worked‐through example of how one can “read” the target tower and match it to the block‐dictionary images without rotating any pieces.  

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1)  ANALYSIS OF THE MAIN TARGET IMAGE  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
•  Overall Count & Layers  
   – The tower uses a total of 8 blocks.  
   – They are stacked in 6 vertical “layers,” from bottom to top:  
     1)  A single yellow rectangular slab.  
     2)  A red “window” layer (with a circular hole in its center).  
     3)  Another single yellow rectangular slab.  
     4)  Two orange columns standing side by side.  
     5)  A third yellow rectangular slab.  
     6)  An orange triangular wedge at the top (the “roof”).  

•  Spatial Arrangement (Bottom to Top)  
   – Layer 1 (base): one horizontal yellow block.  
   – Layer 2 (the red circular “window”): side‐by‐side pairing of two curved red blocks that combine into a square outline with a circular hole.  
   – Layer 3: another horizontal yellow block, directly on top of the red window layer.  
   – Layer 4: two vertical orange cylinders placed next to each other, resting on the third (yellow) slab.  
   – Layer 5: yet another horizontal yellow block, bridging across the two columns.  
   – Layer 6: a single orange wedge forming the “roof” at the very top.  

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2)  SELECTING THE REQUIRED BLOCKS  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
•  Matching Each Visible Shape/Orientation  
   – Yellow horizontal slabs → dictionary block #7, used three times.  
   – Red circular “window” → one copy each of block #3 and block #4.  
     (Together they form the square “window” piece with a circular hole through its center.)  
   – Orange columns (vertical cylinders) → block #11, used twice.  
   – Orange triangular roof wedge → block #16 (it appears in the correct front‐to‐back slope orientation).  

•  Final List of Indices  
   Needed indices (with repeats where required) are:  
   •  7 (×3)  
   •  3 (×1)  
   •  4 (×1)  
   •  11 (×2)  
   •  16 (×1)  

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3)  STEP‐BY‐STEP ASSEMBLY ORDER  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Below is one logical order in which you might place these blocks (from bottom up):

{
  Step1: Move block with index 7
  Step2: Move block with index 3
  Step3: Move block with index 4
  Step4: Move block with index 7
  Step5: Move block with index 11
  Step6: Move block with index 11
  Step7: Move block with index 7
  Step8: Move block with index 16
}

In practice, you would place the bottom yellow #7 first; then set #3 and #4 side by side to make the red “window”; stack the second yellow #7 on top; stand both #11 cylinders vertically; lay the third #7 slab above them; and finally cap the tower with the #16 wedge.
